04497nam a22006855i 9781442656819DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20202006onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426568197 a10.3138/97814426568192doi  a(DE-B1597)551038  a(OCoLC)1163879007  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aB2430.D454bB44 2006eb 7aPHI0260002bisacsh04a1942231 aBell, Jeffrey A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPhilosophy at the Edge of Chaos :bGilles Deleuze and the Philosophy of Difference /cJeffrey A. Bell. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2020] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Systematic Thinking and the Philosophy of Difference -- t2. Ironing Out the Differences: Nietzsche and Deleuze as Spinozists -- t3. Philosophizing the Double Bind: Deleuze Reads Nietzsche -- t4. Thinking Difference: Heidegger and Deleuze on Aristotle -- t5. Thinking and the Loss of System: Derrida and Deleuze on Artaud -- t6. Rethinking System -- tConclusion: Philosophy at the Edge of Chaos -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the early 1960s until his death, French philosopher Gilles Deleuze (1925-1995) wrote many influential works on philosophy, literature, film, and fine art. One of Deleuze's main philosophical projects was a systematic inversion of the traditional relationship between identity and difference. This Deleuzian philosophy of difference is the subject of Jeffrey A. Bell's Philosophy at the Edge of Chaos. Bell argues that Deleuze's efforts to develop a philosophy of difference are best understood by exploring both Deleuze's claim to be a Spinozist, and Nietzsche's claim to have found in Spinoza an important precursor. Beginning with an analysis of these claims, Bell shows how Deleuze extends and transforms concepts at work in Spinoza and Nietzsche to produce a philosophy of difference that promotes and, in fact, exemplifies the notions of dynamic systems and complexity theory. With these concepts at work, Deleuze constructs a philosophical approach that avoids many of the difficulties that linger in other attempts to think about difference. Bell uses close readings of Plato, Aristotle, Spinoza, Nietzsche, Heidegger, Derrida, and Whitehead to illustrate how Deleuze's philosophy is successful in this regard and to demonstrate the importance of the historical tradition for Deleuze. Far from being a philosopher who turns his back on what is taken to be a mistaken metaphysical tradition, Bell argues that Deleuze is best understood as a thinker who endeavoured to continue the work of traditional metaphysics and philosophy.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aDifference (Philosophy) 0aDifference (Philosophy). 0aDifférence (Philosophie). 7aPHILOSOPHY / Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144265681940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442656819423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442656819.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK